##In the human world | a Wuhan psychological consultant thus peel off their own panic

Micro-signal Zairenjian11

Features, with a calm narrative against the cold | phoenix network produced in the human studio

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I spent the 2020 Spring Festival alone in Wuhan.

On January 16, the day before New Year's Eve, my family and friends asked me when I would be returning home. I replied that I was not sure. I am a psychological consultant, this time the accumulation of desk work and study too many courses, so I thought to give myself only three days off, go back to eat a new year meal with my family to return.

January 23, Wuhan "closed" , I want to go back but can not go back.

It wasn't until the second day of the first lunar month that I sat down at my computer to write something and found that only the experience of the word "panic" was the deepest. An online article titled "The Voice of a doctor in Wuhan: Stop Panicking" has a doctor's characteristic detachment and calmness in its tone, but the stop sound especially seems to come from the top of our body, that's where the cerebral CORTEX is.

My panic seemed to seep through every cell of my body, every inch of my skin, breathing in and out. I spent ten days in close proximity with it, and now it's not my brain that's telling me to get rid of it, but I've gone from being completely isolated to being able to spend every day with it, even knowing it.

Every day, I look at my front door and wonder if I should go out wearing a mask. And yet, there was a voice that said, no, I'm afraid to go out. That's when I know my panic is still there, its breath attached to my own. I can't stop the panic, but I can peel it off like a piece of clothing.

Since January 18th, I've been on my own. Early that morning, the child and his father boarded the train leaving Wuhan. Online reports of "pneumonia" are so common that people completely ignore them. Two friends from other places sent relevant texts and pictures, and we just chatted casually. Back then, I didn't even know there was a wire on my mask.

On January 20, I bought two packs of 20 surgical masks at the pharmacy outside my house. The clerk suggested I buy five to keep them ready. I laughed and said No. When I got home, I started learning how to properly wear a mask via video. In the evening, Wuhan reported 136 new cases on January 18 and 19, compared with 17 previously reported. I was a little surprised, but when I looked around and there were so few people out wearing masks, I still didn't care.

On January 22, the 12th of the lunar month, I began to receive orders for flowers, fruit and a few "internet celebrities" , including Harbin's tiramisu cake, russian-style banana cakes and Chengdu's spicy beef jerky. I calculate beautifully, a person's Day also can arrange to have the flavor. In the evening, I did my last video consultation years ago, and the visitor was out of town. A day earlier, she was making a stop at Wuhan High-speed Railway Station and noticed that everyone at the station was wearing face masks, only she was not. She complained to me that, as her consultant, I had not told her in advance that this was the case in Wuhan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The vegetables, which usually stand high in the yard, were looted to pieces.

■ The last time I went out to buy food, it was about five days'worth.

At 10 a.m. on January 23, the city of Wuhan was sealed off. To be honest, it didn't seem that scary to me. Then, all of a sudden, news began to pour in, and there were more voices of doubt than the daily official figures. Schoolmates in the group, the friend circle in succession has the person to say that can not buy the mask, the pharmacy treats the cold, the anti-virus medicine also has been robbed. The supermarket in our community, usually high yard of all kinds of vegetables were robbed to pieces. That was the last time I went grocery shopping, about five days'worth. That day, I took the last express delivery years ago, it is a large bag of soybean milk used to play.

"Fengcheng" , my work and rest imperceptibly become disorder, appetite is not good, do not feel hungry. I only eat two meals a day, and at one or two in the morning I'm constantly scrolling through my phone, looking at anything related to "new crown pneumonia, " not wanting to miss every video retweeted from various unknown groups. The videos of the doctors and nurses breaking down were particularly shocking.

I have a "Chinese and American Class Students Group" , the group has people in Wuhan, there are people scattered across the country. I threw the video of my medical breakdown into the group and said that I didn't want to believe it was true; my classmates in the group also expressed strong shock and worry, and I felt angry when one of them questioned my disbelief.

A classmate in the field told us that her brother a person in Wuhan, a fever, can not find a hospital admission. The classmate cries, she is worried about elder brother.

That night, I don't remember if I had dinner. I couldn't help crying loudly as I lay in bed. I felt as if I had suddenly fallen into another world, with a strong sense of division. The real world was completely shut down, and the Internet became my whole world.

My mind was filled with images of hospitals full of people with fevers and suspected infections, of people dying in hallways unattended, of broken doctors, of no drugs, no beds... I imagined that as soon as I left the house, you get infected, just like in the Zombie world, one bite and you're a Zombie, no longer a normal person.

I didn't tell my family out of town, but I gave them a short description of my life, just in case they were worried. This group of students and a group of friends in the same city became my biggest life support. I wasn't able to start working and studying as planned, I just kept getting caught up in the act of Swiping my phone.

I began to look at myself and notice my own behavior, thoughts, and physical changes. I realized that I was already panicking, just using the primal mechanism of denial to defend myself from my most authentic fears.

The real panic is in the Virus latency. You don't know if you're infected. About 40,000 people left the Hankou Railway Station on the day of the closures, and some people paid high prices for a taxi to try to reach the surrounding city of Wuhan. I do not know the exact number of people who fled Wuhan on the 23rd, but I know that in the hearts of those who fled, did not really leave the panic. The 14-day incubation period is like an invisible cage, a constant feeling of panic that starts on the 23rd and stays with you for the next 14 days.

Everyone will inevitably encounter stress or setbacks in his or her life, but not all of them can not be dealt with. People who are able to cope with stress or frustration and who can regain their mental balance through hard work just experience a panic attack. Once this kind of stress and frustration can not be solved by oneself, and can not be avoided, it will lead to serious psychological imbalance. At this time, people's psychological state will show a period of disintegration and chaos, there will be collapse, crying, seriously out of control behavior, this is the psychological crisis.

In the face of crisis, people's ability to deal with stress and frustration is in direct proportion to their psychological resilience.

When people are cut off from the outside world, they get incomplete information. I have noticed that I am addicted to the news of "new coronary pneumonia" on my phone screen every day. On the one hand, I want to help others' incompleteness, to piece together the information I want to be complete, so that I can have a little sense of control; On the one hand, the body is still in a panic in the middle of the avoidance behavior.

January 24, New Year's Eve that day, after getting up, I very solemnly prepared the new year meal menu. Perhaps the crying on the night of the 23rd had released most of the tension and panic, and I clearly felt mentally relaxed.

When I saw the video of "patients crowding in the hospital" again, and things like a community carrying out patients, covered with white cloth and pulled away by an ambulance, I didn't feel like I was involved anymore. Taken together, the message strikes me as: it's not good, but the problem is patient admissions and medical shortages. Is there any other reason to panic?

I don't think so, either.

At this point, I also noticed that there were people in my circle of friends who followed the news but were not emotionally involved. They still post pictures of the family eating together, and some complain that life is suddenly reduced to eating and sleeping, which is more or less boring. They let me see a part of the real world, in addition to "pneumonia" as well as the New Year and the Spring Festival gala. People talk about "pneumonia" , but "pneumonia" is not the whole story of their lives.

It's still a web-only world, but I seem to have withdrawn from the eye of the storm and found my own rhythm.

January 25, have received relatives and friends of the New Year wishes, many people specifically asked how Wuhan's situation, okay? Greetings from people I've never met. That kind of greeting is like, I don't know you, but I'm watching you. I replied to each one with a "Hug" look.

I was very aware of my emotions and feelings, and my body was completely numb; the slight pain in my throat that had been popping up from time to time the previous day had completely disappeared.

I can clearly recall the impact of those images on the night of the 23rd: Each and every one of us felt a sense of togetherness, of life and death, in a city that has been quarantined. Doctors and nurses are the ones in the eye of the storm, and if one of them breaks down under the pressure, the feeling of collapse spirals through to everyone in the city.

Panic is like a tornado, it started from a few people's crisis, quickly swept up most of the nerve.

My misfortune was that I needed to be alone in the face of the storm, and the loneliness seemed to compound my panic. Fortunately, I was able to withstand the storm. I can take off my panic like I'm taking off a shirt. When I took it off, I saw it right next to me.

I can get back to my normal routine, go to bed by 11 p.m. , wake up at 8 or 9 a.m. , and plan my day.

In the clinical context of psychological crisis intervention, three criteria are required to determine whether a person has experienced a psychological crisis:

1. There are events that have a significant psychological impact;

2. Causes an acute emotional disturbance or cognitive, physical, and behavioral changes that are not consistent with any psychiatric diagnosis;

3. The person or the patient is temporarily unable or unable to cope with the problem using normal problem solving techniques.

The state of clinical crisis can be described as a state of disintegration, in which people suffer setbacks to important life goals and their life cycles and coping strategies are severely disrupted.

The crisis itself is a feeling of fear, shock and sadness from some kind of destruction, not the destruction itself.

If we learn to separate the feelings of fear and shock from the destructive event itself, we leave the center of the storm and land.

■ The flowers are specially prepared for themselves to celebrate the New Year beautifully,

On the morning of January 26, I woke up feeling completely normal, refreshed, weightless and hungry. This is what it feels like when everything goes back to normal.

Looking back, the whole new year, for the taste, I do not feel at all, more like a detention, experienced a purgatory. In retrospect, I have three experiences I would like to share with you:

1. Put The crisis in perspective. A crisis may seem dangerous, but it is not the same as a danger or a disaster. On the one hand, it can lead to serious loss of control or illness, which can lead to killing and suicide. On the other hand, it is also an opportunity. The pain it causes can prompt a person to seek help, and if the person can take advantage of this opportunity to get the right help, not only will he learn from his mistakes, but he will be able to successfully escape the current danger or threat, it also leads to a huge and unforgettable personal growth experience.

2. Use the resources around you. There are a number of targeted self help measures, including meditation exercises, mindfulness audio tutorials, muscle relaxation exercises, home exercise videos, and more. You may not have received professional psychological training, but these simple and effective psychological self-help methods do not need to have deep theoretical knowledge, they are simple and effective, as long as you choose the method that suits you, just calm down and practice, it's a great antidote to panic and anxiety.

3. Don't let yourself be truly alone. Put yourself in a position where you always have the support of friends and family. Generally speaking, the self-limiting period for an emotional crisis is about 6 weeks. During this time, encourage people to talk about their feelings and feelings to those you trust, venting itself can help relieve anxiety and panic attacks.

In addition, the psychological help line can also help you very well.

In this epidemic, the people who had earlier experienced the death of their family members due to illness, as well as the family members of the medical staff in the front line, psychological and therapeutic intervention can help them tide over the psychological crisis relatively smoothly, and hopefully achieve twice the result with half the effort.

January 25 was an important time for the Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China to hold a meeting to report on the prevention and control of pneumonia in the COVID-19, re-study, re-deployment and re-mobilization for epidemic prevention and control, especially for patient treatment. It seems that from that day on, the content that my circle of friends retweets, and the atmosphere in the various groups, began to turn around a negative trend. Medical teams and medical aid supplies from other provinces are arriving in Wuhan, and it is rare to see the personal help-seeking messages from hospitals and doctors. I think that the people and things most deserving of comfort and attention are beginning to be taken seriously, and that the most important aspect of the epidemic is beginning to become rational and orderly, which makes me feel that I have found greater support and protection.

On January 24, the mental crisis intervention hotline in Wuhan, where I had volunteered for three years, resumed answering the phone. The teachers in the group gathered in the online working group to discuss the details of the work, changed the on-site reception to the online reception, collected all kinds of information related to the epidemic, and the hospital also provided us with high-frequency supervision support. More than 30 teachers in the group took turns on duty to deal with the high-intensity telephone crisis intervention.

My shift was scheduled for January 27, and I chose that day because I thought I was fully functional.

The psychological impact of the whole "city closure" incident on the nine million people who, like me, stayed in Wuhan was enormous.

If the outbreak was an accidental disaster, a "lockdown" could mean trauma for a particular group of people. For example, the early experience of abandonment, separation, bereavement, family illness, and so on, "closed city" will stimulate the feelings of early trauma, so that people experience a serious sense of despair, abandonment, depression and anxiety. These traumas may have to wait until the "closure" lifted, the epidemic will gradually eliminate the time will emerge.

I'm trying to tell you from my own experience of the panic, that the pneumonia epidemic and the siege, both of which can have a huge impact on individuals. Don't be ashamed of having extreme emotional reactions. You may be stuck in an unknown disorder for some time to come. Give yourself the deepest understanding. It's okay to be scared, but please encourage yourself to be brave enough to ask for help and support. Please believe that you still have a chance to return to a normal life. (by / Huang Hongling)
